{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601688/1938011101/0041.xml":{"full_text":"IN MIC DEATHS\nCharles Snyder Blamed in\nCrash Costing His and\nWife\u2019s Lives.\nA coroner's jury this afternoon ex\nonerated Harry J. Haynes, 25-year-old\n\u2022enior at George Washington Univer\nsity Medical School, in the deaths of\n*n elderly couple Injured fatally\nChristmas Eve when their automobile\ncollided w'ith his car on Mount Vernon\nboulevard.\nCharles Snyder, 75, of Springfield,\nVa., ho died yesterday in Emergency\nHospital of injuries received in the\ncollision, was blamed by the jury for\nhis own death and that of his wife,\nT4, who was killed in the wreck.\nMr. Haynes, who lives at 707 Rock\nCreek Church road N.W., testified he\n\u2022werved his machine to the right of\nthe highway in a futile effort to avoid\nthe crash.\nAfter completing the Snyder in\nfluest. the jury turned to an inquiry\ninto the death of Miss Mary Clement.\n66, of 223 Pennsylvania avenue S.E.,\nwho died Sunday in Providence Hos\npital of injuries received Saturday\nwhen struck by an automobile at\nThirteenth and D streets N.E. George\nH. Hughes, 21, of 622 Morton place\nN.E., was listed by police as driver.\nCoroner A. Magruder MacDonald\nalso planned to perform an autopsy to\ndetermine whether Charles Rawlings,\n46, of 512 K street S.E., who died in\nProvidence Hospital last night from\nInjuries received Christmas eve, was\nthe victim of a traffic accident.\nMr. Rawlings was picked up at\nSixth street and Virginia avenue S.E.\nand taken to Providence, suffering\nfrom a fractured leg and head in\njuries. Police said at the time that\nhe had been drinking and told them\nhe did not know how he had been\nhurt.\nA hit-and-run motorist struck Er\nnest S. Morrison. 38, of 3314 Mount\nPleasant street N.W. today as he was\nwalking from the curb to the street\ncar loading platform at Georgia ave\nnue and New Hampshire avenue N.W.\nNot believed injured seriously, he was\ntreated at Walter Reed Hospital and\nheld for observation. The striking car\nlater was found abandoned in the 3500\nblock of Eleventh street N.W. Police\nwere searching for the owner.\nT Boy Hurt in Traffic.\nA 5-year-old boy was among sev\neral persons injured in District traffic\naccidents yesterday. He was James E.\nCtewart, 2103 Thirty-seventh street\nN.w\u201e who received a fractured hip\nand a cut lip when struck by an auto\nmobile as he ran from behind a parked\ncar near his home. He was treated\nat Georgetown Hospital. Police said\nAlbert Schatz, 4961 Quebec street\nN-W., was driving the machine.\nBoth her legs were broken below\nthe knee when Mary E. Snowden, 55,\ncolored. 654 Morton street N.W., was\nstruck by an automobile as she was\nwalking across Sixteenth street at\nMeridian place N.W. She was taken 1\nto Emergency Hospital. Police listed\nClyde B. Vaughan, 2321 Eighteenth I\nstreet N.W., as driver of the striking\ncar. i\nHarry Waring, 31, colored, 313 Ninth j\nstreet N.E., was injured painfully I\nwhen his motor cycle, on which the\nbrakes apparently had locked, crashed\nInto an automobile which had stopped\nfor a traffic light in the 100 block\nof Florida avenue N.W. He was\ntreated for heat cuts and a possibly\nfractured ankle at Sibley Hospital.\nINCREASE IN POLICE i\nADVOCATED BY BAR\n\nfederal Association Backs Maj.\nBrown in Drive for 107\nAdditional Officers.\nJoining in the effort to stamp out\ncrime in the District, the Executive\nCouncil of the Federal Bar Associa\ntion last night indorsed the plan of\nMaj. Ernest W. Brown, superintendent\nof police, calling for the addition of\nJ 07 officers to the present force, and\ndirected William R. Vallance, Legisla\ntive Committee chairman, to commu\nnicate with Chairman Ross Collins of\nthe House Subcommittee on District\nAppropriations, and request authoriza\ntion of the personnel increase.\nThe Commissioners\u2019 recommenda\ntion that 31 officers be added to the\ntor(* was described by Mr. Vallance\nM being \u201cinsufficient to handle the\nDistrict's crime problem.\u201d He cited\nSenator Borah's recent statement that\nWashington is \u201cthe second, if not the\ngreatest, crime capital in the world\nThe council expressed appreciation\nof The Star\u2019s current series of articles\nrevealing the extent of organized\ncrime in Washington.\nThe meeting, attended by members\nrepresanting nearly every Government\nAgency in the city, also saw the passage\nCf a recommendation calling for the\nextension of retirement legislation to\ninclude Government employes not al\nready covered.\nft\nMAN SUICIDE b7gAS\nIN APARTMENT HERE\nIn the gas-ffiled kitchen of his\nthird-floor apartment, George E De\nVaughan, 29, of 2526 Seventeenth\n\u2022treet N.W., yesterday took his life\nafter scrawling a brief note to his wife\ncn the back of an envelope.\nMrs. Carolyn De Vaughan told police\n\u25a0be found her husband slumped in a\nchair in the kitchen with the four\ngas Jets on the stove wide open and\nthe doors and windows sealed with\npaper. Accompanied by the janitor\u2019s\nwife, Mrs. Emma Thomas, she said,\n\u25a0he lorced the back door of the apart\nment when she returned from an over\nnight visit and found the apartment\nlocked.\nA note found in the room said.\n^Dearest: I still love you as ever. As\nyour life goes on, give me a thought\nof things that might have been.\nGeorge.\u201d\nA certificate of suicide was issued\nby Coroner A. Magruder MacDonald.\nFuneral services will be field tomor\nrow from the Oak Hill Ch-pel at 3\np,m. Mr. De Vaughan will be buried\nin the Oak Hill Cemetery. He is sur\nvived by his widow and two small\nchildren.\nWill Open Nice Highway.\nBALTIMORE, Jan. 11 (/P).\u2014Govern\nors. of Delaware, Pennsylvania and\nHew Jerffcy have been Invited to at\ni tend ceremonies here Friday for for*\nmal opening of the new Baltimore\nBnuadelphla road. The highway was\nrifled the Gov. Nice highway.\nThree Women Die in Auto Crash\nTtvo-day toll of auto fatalities in Indiana rose to 11 ivith deaths of three women near In\ndianapolis. Their car collided with another. Three other women and a man tvere infixed in\nthe crash. Bodies of the victims are shotvn in front of their wrecked car\n____ \u2014Copyright, A. P. Wirephoto.\n\nStories of Drunkenness De\nclared Used to Discredit\nUnion Groups.\nBy the Associated Press.\nA spokesman for maritime unions\ntold a Senate committee today that\nstories of drunkenness and lack of\ndiscipline among American seamen\nwere being used to discredit union or\nganizations.\nRalph Emerson, who identified him\nself as a legislative representative for\nmaritime unions affiliated with the\nCommittee for Industrial Organiza\ntion, said his groups favored Govern\nment ownership and operation of the\nmerchant marine and opposed any\ncompulsory mediation of labor dis\nputes.\nChairman Copeland of the Senate\nCommerce Committee had shortly be\nfore made public affidavits from five\npassengers of the steamship Hoover\ncharging that part of its crew became\nintoxicated and threatened passengers\nafter the vessel went aground on a\nsmall island near Japan.\nThe affidavits were supplied by the\nState Department from American\nConsul General Addison E. Southard\nat Hong Kong, where the Hoover\u2019s\npassengers were taken.\nMr. Emerson, appearing before the\ncommittee in opposition to numerous\nproposed amendments to the Merchant\nMarine Act, denied the charges con\ntained in the affidavits.\nMeanw'hile. inspectors of the Com\nmerce Department Bureau of Marine\nInspection and Navigation continued\nInvestigation at San Francisco of the\ncharges against the S. S. Hoover crew\nmembers. Officials here said some\nmembers of the crew who recently re\nturned to San Francisco were being\nquestioned and that the hearings\nwould be continued until the full crew\nand the ship's officers and passengers\nhad arrived to give testimony.\nDEATH OF NUCKOLS\nSTILL INVESTIGATED\n\n\u2018Extra-Precautionary\u2019 Step Taken\nin Checking Handwriting\nof Note Left.\nEven though \"convinced beyond a\ndoubt\u201d that Carroll P. (Nubby) Nuck\nols took his own life, police are still\nchecking the possibility of a different\nending to the career of the 38-year\nold gambler.\nThis was revealed today by Inspec\ntor Bernard W. Thompson, chief of\ndetectives, who said the handwriting\non a note left by Nuckols was being\ncompared with other samples of his\npenmanship. The comparison is ex\npected to be completed late today or\ntomorrow.\n\u201cWe are Just making a routine\u2014\nbut exhaustive\u2014investigation, as we\ndo in every case, despite the fact that\nthere seems to be no reason for it,\"\nthe detective chief said.\nCapt. Ira Keck, assistant to the\nInspector, also emphasized that the\n\u2019check\" was Just an \u201cextra-precau\ntionary\u201d step.\nDiscussing the possibility that some\none could have entered Nuckols\u2019 Con\nnecticut avenue apartment\u2014where the\ngambler was found shot through the\nhead Saturday night\u2014Capt. Keck said\nthere were \u201cpositively\u201d only two keys\nto a heavy grill door to the place.\nNuckols had one on his person and\nhis wife, who discovered the body,\nthe other, he said.\nU. S.-CANADIAN GROUPS\nSTUDY AIR PROBLEMS\nDelegates to the United States\nCanadian aviation conference at the\nState Department have divided them\nselves into subcommittees for consid\neration of a number of outstanding\nair transport, communications and\nweather problems in connection with\noperations across the border.\nThree of these subcommittees are\nIn session today. They were created\nto consider aeronautical arrange\nments between the two governments,\nthe allocation of radio frequencies\nand the establishment of communica\ntions for handling weather and air\nnavigation.\nIt was anticipated the remainder\n>f the conference will be carried on\nthrough the subcommittees. A tenta\ntive program for the remainder of\nthe conference has been approved by\nbeads of the two delegations, V. I.\nSmart, deputy minister of the\nCanadian Department of Transport,\nwd R. Walton Moore, counselor of\nthe United States States Department^,\nm\nMRS. ROOSEVELT LEADS\nTRIBUTE TO MME. CURIE\nBiography of Scientist Presented\nto Jules Henry by Cancer\nControl Society.\nMrs. Franklin D. Roosevelt and a\nnumber of other prominent members\nof the Women's Field Army of the\nAmerican Society for the Control of\nCancer paid tribute today to the mem\nory of Mme. Marie Curie with the\npresentation of a specially-bound vol\nj ume of the biography of the great\nj woman scientist to Jules Henry. Min\nister Plenipotentiary of France.\n\"We are indebted to Mme. Curie\nnot only for her great discovery, but\nfor her great life,\" Mrs. Roosevelt\nsaid. \"We are fortunate, indeed, in\nhaving this brilliant biography writ\nten by her daughter and so trans\nlated as to lose none of its spirit, of\nbeauty. It should prove an inspira\ntion to American women in their\ncampaign against cancer.\u201d\nThe presentation was made at the\nFrench Embassy by Mrs. Marjorie B.\nIllig of Onset, Maas., national com\nmander of the Women's Field Army,\nwhich includes 100.000 members.\nA. P. SIGNS PAY PACT\nWITH TELEGRAPHERS\nAgreement Covering Wages and i\nWorking Conditions Negotiated\nWith A. F. of L. Union.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 11.\u2014An agree\nment covering wages and working con\nditions in the traffic department of\nthe Associated Press was signed yes\nterday by representatives of the Asso\nciated Press and the Commercial Te\nlegraphers\u2019 Union.\nUnder the agreement, the C. T. U\u201e\nwhich is affiliated with the American\nFederation of Labor, is recognized as\nthe sole union bargaining agenev for\nemployes in the traffic department en\ngaged in the leased wire, radio and\nwirephoto service. There is no pro\nvision for a closed or preferential shop,\nbut it is provided that that subject\nwill be taken up later.\nThe right of seniority is recognized\nunder each classification, ability and\nfitness permitting or being equal. The\npresent schedule of work hours is con\ntinued and wage increases granted in\nsome classes. A Grievance Committee\nis established, and it is agreed that\ndisputes arising qnder the agreement\nshall be arbitratei\nIn cases where positions are elim\ninated, the employe affected is to be\ngiven two weeks\u2019 notice and an ad\nditional two weeks wages if he has been\nin full-time service for one year or\nmore.\nThe agreement becomes effective\nimmediately and remains in effect un\ntil March 31, 1939. The Associated\nPress also announced that the wage\nscales and conditions set forth would\nbe applicable to all employes in the\ntraffic department, regardless of\nwhether they are members of the C. T.\nU., and that the provisions for\u2019 sev\nerance pay established January 1 last,\nequal to or exceeding the agreement,\nwould be continued.\nD. C. ENGINEER DISTRICT\nGRANTED $24,000 MORE\nWoodring Announces Allotment\nfor Examinations, Surveys\nand Contingencies.\nAllotment of $24,000 of additional\nfunds for examinations, surveys and\ncontingencies in the Washington Army\nEngineer district was announced to\nday by Secretary of War Woodring.\nThe allotment will be used for prep\naration of reports on examinations and\nsurveys in the Potomac River Valley\nauthorized by Congress and for mis\ncellaneous examinations and surveys\nfor which specific allotments have\nnot been made.\nIt also will be used to finance com\npilation of commercial statistics con\ncerning Potomac River trafllc; reports\non bridges and other structures over\nnavigable waters and routine investiga\ntions, the War Department explained.\nU. S. GROUP TO MEET\nPanel Discussion of Personnel\nPractices Scheduled.\nImprovement in personnel prac\ntices suggested by Federal workers will\nbe the topic for a panel discussion at\na meeting in the Government audi\ntorium tonight under the auspices of\nUie Council of Personnel Administra\ntion.\nThe chairman of the panel is F. A.\nBirgfeld, chief clerk of the Treasury,\nand its members: E. J. Gardner, Com\nmerce; C. C. Hathaway, civil service;\nW. L. Mitchell, social security, and R.\nC. Smith, Labor.\nTbs program will start at t^doek.\nBorah and O\u2019Mahoney Cite\nValue of Corporate\nLicensing Plan.\nBy the Associated Press.\nAmong the proposals being dis\ncussed by Congressmen and admin\nistration officials for strengthening\nanti-trust laws is the Borah\nO'Mahoney bill to require Federal\nlicensing of interstate corporations.\nThe following article explains the\nbill's provisions.\nB\u00bb the Associated Press.\nSponsors of a Federal corporation\nlicensing program declared today it\nnot only would break up monopolies,\nbut would impose desirable labor\nstandards.\nSenators Borah, Republican, of\nIdaho and O'Mahoney, Democrat, of\nWyoming, co-authors of the measure,\nsaid it was based on this principle:\n\u201cThat since the Constitution gives\nto the Federal Government the power\nto regulate commerce among the\nStates, and since this commerce i$\nnow chiefly carried on by artificial\nagencies called corporations, the pow\ners, functions and duties of these\nagencies should be prescribed by the\nFederal Government.\"\nAs a prerequisite to doing business\nin interstate commerce, the bill pro\nvides that corporations would have to\nobtain licenses, or charters, from the\nFederal Trade Commission. Its mem\nbership would be increased from five\nto nine.\nBefore the commission would issue\na license, a corporation would have to\nprovide detailed information on its\noperations, organization. financial\nstructure, salaries and securities.\nA license could be denied if the com\nmission found that a corporation was\nviolating the existing anti-trust laws\nor was monopolizing or conspiring to\nmonopolize any part of commerce.\nEach license would contain \u2018\u2018such\nterms and conditions as the commis\nsion shall prescribe\u201d as necessary to\ncarry out purposes of the act. Licenses\ncould be revoked if the conditions\nwere violated; revocation could be ap\npealed to the courts.\nThe bill would prevent discrimina\ntion in rates of pay against women\nemployes who performed services \"ap\nproximately equivalent to those per\nformed by male employes.\u201d\nIt would prohibit work by persons\nunder 16 years erf age or the employ\nment of those under 18 in hazardous\noccupations.\nEmployes would be guaranteed the\nright to bargain collectively. To ren\nder such bargaining more effective,\nthe Trade Commission could obtain\nfrom licensed corporations cost, price\nand other data.\nIt also could recommend to Con\ngress establishment of minimum wage\nscales for industries where \"abuses\nhave not been eliminated through col\nlective bargaining.\u201d\nARMY FLYERS KILLED\nBarksdale Field Plane Crashes at\nGrandview, Tex.\nGRANDVIEW, Tex., Jan. 11 UP).\u2014\nArmy officers investigated today the\ncrash of a Barksdale Field plane yes\nterday in which Lt. Frank Thompson\nof Columbus, Ohio, pilot, and W. T.\nMathews, a non-commissioned officer,\nwere instantly killed.\nThe ship* nosed into heavy timber\nabout J\u2019/a miles from Grandview.\nNEW U. POLICY\n\u201cModification\u201d Best Way to\nBusiness Revival, New\nYorker Says.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. Jan. 11.\u2014Winthrop\nW. Aldrich, chairman cf the board of\nthe Chase National Bank, declared\ntoday \"a prompt and adequate mod\nification of Government policy regard\ning the capital market would make a\nmajor contribution to business re\nvival.\u201d\nThe banker made the suggestion in\nthe course of an address at the an\nnual meeting of the bank's stock\nholders.\nHe directed sharp criticism at the\nFederal capital gains tax, the un\ndistributed profits tax and the struc\nture of Federal regulation affecting\nsecurities.\nReferring to statements he made\nlast October charging excessive thin\nness of the stock market was due\npartly to Securities and Exchange\nCommission rules, he declared \"the\nadequate rectification of this condi\ntion of the stock market remains one\nof the most urgent needs of the cap\nital market of the United States.\u201d\n\"Helpful Interchange.\u201d\nAldrich said his discussion was of\nfered with \u201cthe hope of contributing\nto the helpful interchange of opinion,\nnow going on between Washington\nand the business and financial com\nmunity.\n\u201cTaxation for debt retirement,\"\nsaid Aldrich, \u201cis a source of capital\nas it returns capital to investors in\nGovernment securities, who, in gen\neral, reinvest in productive enter\nprises. But for the past few years,\nand even currently, this source of\ncapital has ceased on balance, an.1\ngovernmental bodies Instead, have\nbeen absorbing the capital of the\ncountry through increasing the public\ndebt instead of retiring it.\u201d\nThe capital gains tax \u201cat anything\nlike the high rates of the upper brack\nets,\u201d he charged, \u201csimilarly causes\nthe dissipation of capital.\u201d Urging re\npeal of the undistributed profits tax,\nAldrich asserted it \u201chas dealt a devas\ntating blow\u201d to one of \"the most im\nportant of all our sources of capital\u201d\u2014\nreinvestment of corporate profits in\ncorporate enterprise.\nThe bank's net earnings for 1937\nwere reported at *15,016,494, equal to\n*2.03 a share of capital stock.\nPerkins Sees Improvement.\nComplete recovery depends on so\nlution of a number of problems, but\nalready improvement is in sight, James\nH. Perkins, chairman of the National\nCity Bank of New York and City\nBank Farmers Trust Co., asserted in\nhis report to stockholders.\nHe listed as causes of the slump\nstocking-up of Inventories last Spring.\nincreased cost of production through i\ntaxation and added wage burdens, the\nending of inflationary support pre\nviously given by the Government's\ndeficit financing and \u201cthe effect of\nexisting uncertainties in retarding the\nflow of savings into new industries\nand private enterprise.\u201d He added:\n\u201cI do not mean to imply, in pre\nsenting these difficult problems, that\na resumption of the business recovery\nwill await their complete solution. On\nthe contrary, the correction of inven\ntories is proceeding rapidly in many\nquarters, and it appears that within\na short time this cause of recession\nwill be largely removed.\n\u201cThe pressure of declining volume\nand profit is inducing other changes\nin the direction of greater efficiency\nand lowered costs which are laying\nthe basis for improvement. But I\nhold that these are key problems. As\nprogress is made toward solving them\nthe business situation will be propor\ntionately improved.\u201d\n\nCITY NEWS IN BRIEF.\nTODAY.\nMeeting, Board of Directors.\u2019Society\nfor Prevention of Blindness, Y. W. C.\nA., 4:45 p.m.\nMeeting. Society for Philosophical\nInquiry, National Museum, 4:45 p.m.\nMeeting. Federal Bar Association,\nMayflower Hotel, 5 p.m.\nDinner meeting, Plumbers\u2019 Guild,\nInc., Willard Hotel, 6 p.m.\nDinner, American Institute of Elec\ntrical Engineers, Raleigh Hotel, 6 p.m.\nSupper and meeting, Women\u2019s Na\ntional Press Club, Willard Hotel, 6:30\np.m.\nDinner, Graduate Nurses\u2019 Associa\ntion, Lafayette Hotel, 7:30 p.m.\nSupper and meeting, German Club,\nLafayette Hotel, 8 p.m.\nMeeting, Daughters of Penelope,\nWardman Park Hotel, 8 p.m.\nMeeting, junior section. District Bar\nAssociation, Mayflower Hotel, 8 p.m.\nTOMORROW.\nLuncheon, Gyro Club, Lafayette\nHotel, 12:30 p.m.\nLuncheon, Lions Club, Mayflower\nHotel, 12:30 p.m.\nLuncheon, Monarch Club, Willard\nHotel, 12:30 p.m.\nLuncheon, Rotary Club, Willard Ho\ntel, 12:30 p.m.\nMeeting, Transportation Club, Ham\nilton Hotel, 6:30 p.m.\nDinner, National Sojourners, La\nfayete Hotel, 6:30 p.m.\nMeeting, Izaak Walton League, Ra\nleigh Hotel, 7:30 p.m.\nMeeting, Catholic Thought Associa\ntion, Willard Hotel, 7:30 p.m.\nMeeting, Young Democratic Club,\nWillard Hotel, 8 p.m.\nCard party and dance, Mizrachi\nZionist Organization, Willard Hotel,\n8 p.m.\nWestinghouse\nAir-Conditioning\nNow Being Installed\nCapitol Theater\nWinchester, Virginia\nA Warner Bros. House\nCombustioneer Corporation\nFred A. Hessick, President\nUndivided Responsibility\nSales, En|ineerinf, Installation\nMetal Shop and Service\nA\nPOWER SUIT DROPPED\nThe Community Public Service\nCo. of Texas, which several months\nago obtained an injunction in Dis\ntrict Court delaying Federal grants\nto the Lower Colorado River Au\nthority for public electrical develop\nment, today consented to dismissal\nof its suit.\nThis action was taken in the light\nof the Supreme Court decision two\nweeks ago upholding the W. P. A. pro\ngram for financing public power de\nvelopments in the Alabama Power Co.\nand Duke Power Co. cases. Some\ntwo score similar cases are pending\nin District Court and most are ex\npected to be dropped.\nMEMORIAL LECTURE\nTICKETS GOING OUT\nFirst of Bronson Cutting Series to\nBe Delivered Monday in\nConstitution Hall.\nTickets are being mailed this week\nfor the Bronson Cutting memorial\nlectures, the first of which will be\ndelivered next Monday night in Con\nstitution Hall.\nThe first speaker will be Bruce\nBliven, editor of New Republic Maga\nzine, who will discuss \u201cDemocracy\nand Public Opinion.\u201d The second\nwill be on February 7, when Dr. Ed\nwin Borchard of Yale University Law\nSchool will talk on \u201cDemocracy and\nForeign Policy.\u201d\nAll tickets to the lectures are com\nplimentary and call for reserved seats.\nThe lectures are endowed by Mrs.\nBayard Cutting in memory of her\nson, the late Senator Bronson Cut\nting of New Mexico.\nRequests already have been received\nfor all tickets, and the hall is ex\npected to be filled. The first ticket\ncovers the first two lectures. The\nlargest blocks have been requested by\nmembers of the legations and embas\nsies and their staffs and members of\nCongress and their aides.\nThe third and final lecture will be\ndelivered March 21 by Dr. C. A.\nDykstra, president of the University\nof Wisconsin, whose subject will be\n\"Democracy and Education.\u201d\n\nDeath Found Accidental.\nCoroner A. Magruder MacDonald\nyesterday held accidental the death\nof Louella Stacks, 57, colored, 625\nK street N.W., who was injured fa\ntally when she jumped from a second\nstory window at Gallinger Hospital\nSunday night. She had been treat- j\ned at the hospital since December 5\nfor severe high blood pressure, which\nphysicians said caused her to suffer\nperiods of confusion.\nFRANCE PROTESTS\nMISSIONBOMBING\nOne Monk Killed in Attack\nJanuary 9 at Nanning,\nSouth China.\nB\u00bb the Associated Press.\nPARIS, Jan. 11.\u2014The French gov\nernment today Instructed Its Ambassa\ndor at Tolcio to deliver an \"energetic\nprotest\" against the bombing of a\nFrench Catholic mission at Nanning,\nSouth China, by Japanese warplanes\nJanuary 9.\nA communique announcing the pro\ntest said one French monk (Shanghai\ndispatches identified him as Father\nMartin) was killed and another\nwounded in the attack against the mis\nsion buildings.\nFrench Zone Affected.\nInformed observers believed the\nFrench foreign office acted with vigor\nbecause Nanning is capital of Kwangsi\nProvince, adjoining French Indo-China\nand considered a zone of special\nFrench interest.\nThe attack brought new tension into\nFranco-Japanese relations, already\nstrained as a result of Incidents of the\nChinese-Japanese war.\nIt followed a dispute disclosed two\nmonths ago over use of the French\nrailway from Indo-Chlna into tha\nChinese Province of Yunnan as a car\nrier for arms for the Chinese govern\nment. As a result of strong Japanese\ndiplomatic representatives\u2014and ac\ncording to .some French sources actual\nthreats\u2014France agreed to forbid use\nof the railway for such shipments.\nReactions Contrasted.\nObservers contrasted the promptness\nwith which France acted over the\nKwangsl attack and the calmness of\nthe Paris foreign ministry over a\nthreatening clash between Japanese\ntroops and police of the French conces\nsion at Shanghai January 8.\nThe foreign ministry declined to\ndisclose what was demanded of Tokio\nin connection with the Nanning bomb\ning, but indicated hope the affair could\nbe settled satisfactorily through diplo\nmatic channels.\n$14 WAGE IS FIXED\nU. S. to Require That Scale in\nHandkerchief Contracts.\nSecretary Perkins fixed today a\nminimum wage of (14 a week and a\nmaximum work week of 40 hours as\na requirement in filling Government\ncontracts of (10,000 or more in the\nhandkerchief industry.\nThe ruling, effective January 26,\nwas made under provisions of the\nWalsh-Healey Government contract\nact.\n'The Paths of Happiness b Sentiment Lead to Shah b Shah\"\nJBHL\nWednesday Only\n3 5% off\nAll Toilet Sets\nYour unrestricted choice from a fine\nassortment of Comb, Brush and Mir\nror Sets. Sterling, Gold-filled and\nEnameled Designs to delight every\nwoman. Regular *10.50 to *35,00\nvalues for as little as *6.8n to *22.75\u2014\nTOMORROW ONLY I\nShah Shah\nJEWELERS SILVERSMITHS\n921 F Street N.W.\nI. Shah Known to Washington Over a Quarter-Century\nM\nSloane\u2019s \u2014711 Twelfth Streetan^anv\n.A\nIt Just Happened\n-and cannot hope to be repeated\n\nSpecial Purchase of\nAmerican Oriental Rugs\nSize, 9x12\nAll perfect\u2014reproductions of Persian mas\nterpieces that hold treasured place in famous\nmuseums and private collections.\nThey have the rich deep pile and lustrous\nsheen of the genuine Orientals. Product of\nthe makers of Gulistan Rugs.\nDivided into two groups:\nRegular Price, $98.50 Regular Price, $79.50\nChoice Choice\n*75 <59\u00ae\nI\nW. &J. Sloane 711 Twelfth St.\nCourtesy Perking, Capitol Garage Convenient Charge Accounts","height":"31360","width":"22520"}}
